ce:section.ce:para:
The optical properties of as-prepared CQDs and Er-CQDs were investigated by UV–vis absorption spectra and fluorescent spectra (Fig. 2
                         and Fig. 3
                        ). The UV–vis absorption spectra of CQDs and Er-CQDs are presented in Fig. 2. It can be found that the CQDs show obvious absorption bands from UV region to blue region, which generate from the π-π*, n-π* and surface states transition. As well known, the light absorption of materials relates to the band gap between the excited states and ground states, while the energy levels of the electronic states are determined by the intrinsic electronic structure of the materials. The π-π* transition originates from sp2 domains implying the existence of a large π-electron system in the structure of CQDs. The n-π* transition and the surface trap states are related to the C=O, C-N and other surface groups. From the UV–vis absorption spectrum of Er-CQDs, it can also be seen that Er-CQDs exhibits strong absorption from UV region to blue region. Unlike the CQDs, the Er-CQDs displays much stronger light absorption, at the same time, gives some absorption peaks in visible region from 480 to 700 nm. It indicates that the introduction of Er into CQDs has broadened the light absorption range, especially, in visible-light range.
